name: lauric acid, phenyl ester
Reason: The compound is based on lauric acid and phenol as two major structural units. The lauric acid backbone has a melting point around 44 °C, but esterification with phenol will tend to reduce this melting point due to the ester group providing less intermolecular hydrogen bonding compared to the carboxylic acid group. Phenol has a melting point of 41 °C, and its introduction as a phenyl ring should provide additional rigidity to the structure which can increase the melting point. The ester group is expected to lower the melting point by about -20 °C from the lauric acid backbone. The phenyl group is expected to contribute a slight increase, possibly around +5 °C, due to increased pi-pi interactions and van der Waals forces.
